<webwork-reps version="2" webwork2_major_version="2" webwork2_minor_version="20" xml:id="extracted-section-solving-rational-equations-10-11-4" assembly-id="section-solving-rational-equations-10-11-4">
  <static seed="1468" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations28.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{7}{r+5}-\frac{2}{r+4}}={\frac{8}{r^{2}+9r+20}}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{-2\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{\left(r+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+4\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{7}{r+5}-\frac{2}{r+4}} \amp = {\frac{8}{r^{2}+9r+20}} \\
  {\frac{7}{r+5}-\frac{2}{r+4}} \amp = {\frac{8}{\left(r+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+4\right)}} \\
  {\frac{7}{r+5}\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+4\right)-\frac{2}{r+4}\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+4\right)} \amp = {\frac{8}{\left(r+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+4\right)}\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+4\right)} \\
  {7\mathopen{}\left(r+4\right)-2\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)} \amp = {8} \\
  {7r+28-2r-10} \amp = {8} \\
  {5r+18} \amp = {8} \\
  {5r} \amp = -10 \\
  \frac{5 r}{5} \amp = \frac{-10}{5} \\
  r \amp = -2
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p>For this example, it<rsq/>s easy to see we must exclude <m>-5</m> and <m>-4</m> from the solution set. These values are not in the solution set we got, so the final solution is <m>r=-2</m>.</p>
</solution>
